@flener pointed out that there's a memory leak when executing:

````cpp
auto ttf = Label::createWithTTF("TTF", "fonts/Marker Felt.ttf", 24);
ttf->setPosition(visibleSize/2);
ttf->setOverflow(Label::Overflow::SHRINK);
ttf->setDimensions(ttf->getContentSize().width,ttf->getContentSize().height);
this->addChild(ttf);
````

Turns out `valgrind` also finds a memory leak when doing the same but with bitmap fonts:

````cpp
auto bmf = Label::createWithBMFont("fonts/konqa32.fnt", "BMF");
bmf->setPosition(visibleSize/4);
bmf->setOverflow(Label::Overflow::SHRINK);
bmf->setDimensions(bmf->getContentSize().width,bmf->getContentSize().height);
addChild(bmf);
````

This pull request fixes #17639. See @flener's report [in the forums](http://discuss.cocos2d-x.org/t/bug-report-memory-leak-on-label-setdimentions/36018) for more information. Both cases boil down to be the same issue.

Issue #17380 could be related.

- cocos2d-x version: v3.15, git commit c27cca3d17
- devices test on:
- developing environments
   - GCC

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Create a new C++ project, compile it in debug mode and run `valgrind` against it:

````shell
cocos new -l c++ websockettest
cd websockettest
cocos compile -p linux -j`nproc`
valgrind --tool=memcheck --leak-check=full --show-leak-kinds=all bin/debug/linux/MyGame
````

2. You'll get the following report:
````
==7952== LEAK SUMMARY:
==7952==    definitely lost: 0 bytes in 0 blocks
==7952==    indirectly lost: 0 bytes in 0 blocks
==7952==      possibly lost: 1,352 bytes in 18 blocks
==7952==    still reachable: 112,392 bytes in 983 blocks
==7952==                       of which reachable via heuristic:
==7952==                         newarray           : 1,536 bytes in 16 blocks
==7952==         suppressed: 0 bytes in 0 blocks
````

3. Add the following to `Classes/HelloWorldScene.cpp` under `USING_NS_CC`:

````cpp
#include "network/WebSocket.h"
class WebSocketClientDelegate : public network::WebSocket::Delegate
{
	public:
		//virtual ~WebSocketClientDelegate();
		static WebSocketClientDelegate* getInstance()
		{
			static WebSocketClientDelegate instance;
			return &instance;
		}
		virtual void onOpen(network::WebSocket* ws) override
		{
			CCLOG("onOpen");
		}
		virtual void onMessage(network::WebSocket* ws, const network::WebSocket::Data& data) override
		{
			CCLOG("onMessage");
		}
		virtual void onClose(network::WebSocket* ws) override
		{
			CCLOG("onClose");
		}
		virtual void onError(network::WebSocket* ws, const network::WebSocket::ErrorCode& error) override
		{
			CCLOG("onError");
		}
};
````

And under `HelloWorld::init`, add the following:

```cpp
auto websocket_test = new network::WebSocket();
if(!websocket_test->init(*WebSocketClientDelegate::getInstance(), "ws://127.0.0.1:7681")) 
{
	delete websocket_test;
	websocket_test = nullptr;
}
````

4. Recompile and run `valgrind` against the executable. You'll get the following:

````
==9680== LEAK SUMMARY:
==9680==    definitely lost: 24 bytes in 1 blocks
==9680==    indirectly lost: 0 bytes in 0 blocks
==9680==      possibly lost: 1,784 bytes in 19 blocks
==9680==    still reachable: 178,390 bytes in 1,041 blocks
==9680==                       of which reachable via heuristic:
==9680==                         newarray           : 1,536 bytes in 16 blocks
==9680==         suppressed: 0 bytes in 0 blocks
```` 

The above report stands whether or not the connection is succesful, wether or not `delete websocket_test` was executed at some point, or even when `WebSocket::closeAllConnections()` gets called, like the following:

````cpp
this->scheduleOnce([] (float dt) 
				   {
					   cocos2d::Director::getInstance()->getScheduler()->performFunctionInCocosThread(
						   [] ()
						   {
							   network::WebSocket::closeAllConnections();
						   }
						   );
				   },
				   2.5f, "key"
				  );
````

This last case also seems to incur in another memory leak:

````
==18809== LEAK SUMMARY:
==18809==    definitely lost: 48 bytes in 2 blocks
==18809==    indirectly lost: 8 bytes in 1 blocks
==18809==      possibly lost: 1,784 bytes in 19 blocks
==18809==    still reachable: 178,358 bytes in 1,039 blocks
==18809==                       of which reachable via heuristic:
==18809==                         newarray           : 1,536 bytes in 16 blocks
==18809==         suppressed: 0 bytes in 0 blocks
````

From the `valgrind` report on this last case, there are three lines in particular that caught my attention, all of which can be traced back to `websocket_test` which was initialized above.

````
==15309==    by 0x9D5C6D: cocos2d::network::WebSocket::WebSocket() (WebSocket.cpp:531)
==15309==    by 0x9D5C27: cocos2d::network::WebSocket::WebSocket() (WebSocket.cpp:528)
==15309==    by 0x9D640D: cocos2d::network::WebSocket::init(cocos2d::network::WebSocket::Delegate const&, std::__cxx11::basic_string<char, std::char_traits<char>, std::allocator<char> > const&, std::vector<std::__cxx11::basic_string<char, std::char_traits<char>, std::allocator<char> >, std::allocator<std::__cxx11::basic_string<char, std::char_traits<char>, std::allocator<char> > > > const*, std::__cxx11::basic_string<char, std::char_traits<char>, std::allocator<char> > const&) (WebSocket.cpp:624)
````

Hi, cocos2d-x team!

Quite a long time ago, you guys announced a [new renderer pipeline roadmap](http://www.cocos2d-x.org/wiki/Cocos2d_v30_renderer_pipeline_roadmap). So far, I can see that the main structure is already functional for the cocos2dx version I'm working with (v3.13). However, some of the major features are still missing, like the full featured command keys:

![alt text][logo]

[logo]: http://www.cocos2d-x.org/attachments/download/5084 "RenderCommand keys"

The current sorting by `globalZOrder` works fine and already gives a nice performance improvement (see code below). However, all other nodes that have `globalZOrder = 0` (including all `Widget` classes) still use the [old rendering optimization highly dependent on `Node` hierarchy](https://github.com/cocos2d/cocos2d-objc/wiki/Cocos2D-Render-Order-and-Batching):

```c++
void RenderQueue::sort()
{
    // Don't sort _queue0, it already comes sorted
    std::sort(std::begin(_commands[QUEUE_GROUP::TRANSPARENT_3D]), std::end(_commands[QUEUE_GROUP::TRANSPARENT_3D]), compare3DCommand);
    std::sort(std::begin(_commands[QUEUE_GROUP::GLOBALZ_NEG]), std::end(_commands[QUEUE_GROUP::GLOBALZ_NEG]), compareRenderCommand);
    std::sort(std::begin(_commands[QUEUE_GROUP::GLOBALZ_POS]), std::end(_commands[QUEUE_GROUP::GLOBALZ_POS]), compareRenderCommand);
}

static bool compareRenderCommand(RenderCommand* a, RenderCommand* b)
{
    return a->getGlobalOrder() < b->getGlobalOrder();
}
```

![alt text][nodes]

[nodes]: https://camo.githubusercontent.com/ed2f14db7ae31400107bd6f2831d0e570bfaa920/687474703a2f2f66696c65732e736c656d62636b652e6e65742f74656d702f436f636f73324452656e6465724f726465722e737667 "Old drawing order, hierarchy dependent"

I'd like to know how this roadmap is going, what you still plan to do and what have you discarded.

Thanks!
